messages.content: Though Daisy and Gatsby both live in a world of excess, yet they still live in different worlds. While Daisy evidently lives in one of order and tradition, where brides receive lavish, feminine gifts and act as the proper housewife after marriage, Gatsby lives in a world where young single women seek to entice random men of status at parties. To Daisy, his world must seem like a vulgar rebuke to everything sheâs had to suffer through for the sake of propriety and family duty - domesticity, commitment to a man who doesnât even love her, etc; in other words, Gatsbyâs life of excess seems overly free and thus irresponsible, because to Daisy a responsible and dutiful life is one where you commit to misery.
